<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="534" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,259,429]" pageId="11" pageNumber="534">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,399,295,321]" pageId="11" pageNumber="534">Male terminalia.</emphasis>
The aedeagus of this species is very similar to that of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Duda" authorityYear="1927" box="[1018,1173,296,321]" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Psathyrellaceae" genus="Drosophila" kingdom="Fungi" order="Agaricales" pageId="11" pageNumber="534" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="sturtevanti">
<emphasis box="[1018,1173,296,321]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="534">D. sturtevanti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1190,1313,295,321]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="11.[151,250,1454,1478]" captionTargetBox="[162,1424,463,1420]" captionTargetId="figure-101@11.[151,1436,453,1431]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 9. Scanning electron micrographs of D. lehrmanae male terminalia. (A) Ventral and dorsal view of terminalia (526 x magnification). (B) Lateral view of aedeagus and phallapodeme (1.020 x magnification). Arrow heads = “caudal” projection. Image from Madi-Ravazzi et al. (2021). (C) Dorsal view of aedeagus (2.260 x magnification). The imagens are from STV-like strain. Abbreviations in Table 1." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5649980" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5649980/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="534">Fig. 9A–C</figureCitation>
), however, the striking characteristic that differs it from the other species is the relatively short aedeagal apex (
<figureCitation box="[1270,1392,331,357]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="11.[151,250,1454,1478]" captionTargetBox="[162,1424,463,1420]" captionTargetId="figure-101@11.[151,1436,453,1431]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 9. Scanning electron micrographs of D. lehrmanae male terminalia. (A) Ventral and dorsal view of terminalia (526 x magnification). (B) Lateral view of aedeagus and phallapodeme (1.020 x magnification). Arrow heads = “caudal” projection. Image from Madi-Ravazzi et al. (2021). (C) Dorsal view of aedeagus (2.260 x magnification). The imagens are from STV-like strain. Abbreviations in Table 1." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5649980" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5649980/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="534">Fig. 9B, C</figureCitation>
). In addition to this, the lower base of the aedeagus has a less pronounced projection than that of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Duda" authorityYear="1927" box="[1218,1374,368,393]" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Psathyrellaceae" genus="Drosophila" kingdom="Fungi" order="Agaricales" pageId="11" pageNumber="534" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="sturtevanti">
<emphasis box="[1218,1374,368,393]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="534">D. sturtevanti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="11.[151,250,1454,1478]" captionTargetBox="[162,1424,463,1420]" captionTargetId="figure-101@11.[151,1436,453,1431]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 9. Scanning electron micrographs of D. lehrmanae male terminalia. (A) Ventral and dorsal view of terminalia (526 x magnification). (B) Lateral view of aedeagus and phallapodeme (1.020 x magnification). Arrow heads = “caudal” projection. Image from Madi-Ravazzi et al. (2021). (C) Dorsal view of aedeagus (2.260 x magnification). The imagens are from STV-like strain. Abbreviations in Table 1." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5649980" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5649980/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="534">Fig. 9B</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
